About us

Our Journey in Advancing Health and Research.

Rinda Ubuzima continues the legacy of Projet Ubuzima, an organization founded in 2001 by Prof. Jope Lange of the University of Amsterdam. Strengthened in 2004 by Prof. Janneke van de Wijgert and colleagues from IATEC, the organization spent 15 years building clinical research capacity and infrastructure. Now a national NGO based in Kigali, Rinda Ubuzima operates a research clinic and laboratory, specializing in HIV, reproductive health, and malaria studies, while also leading community engagement and outreach programs.

Services

What we do

Find out which one of our services fit the needs of your project

Clinical Trials Management

Rinda Ubuzima specializes in designing and conducting clinical trials, particularly in the fields of HIV, reproductive health, and malaria.

Research Clinic Operations

The organization runs a research clinic in Kigali, providing infrastructure and support for participant care and study implementation.

Laboratory Services

Equipped with a dedicated laboratory, Rinda Ubuzima conducts diagnostic testing and sample analysis to support its clinical research activities.

Community Engagement & Outreach

Beyond research, Rinda Ubuzima implements community outreach programs to raise awareness and promote public health initiatives.

Capacity Building & Training

The organization invests in training healthcare professionals and researchers, enhancing local expertise in clinical research and laboratory practices.

Public Health Research

Rinda Ubuzima conducts studies that inform public health policies and interventions, contributing to evidence-based healthcare solutions.

Microbicide Trial

In preparation for microbicide trials in Rwanda, researchers conducted focus group discussions with various groups, including married women, unmarried women, sex workers, students, older women, and men in both urban and rural areas. Vaginal hygiene practices were common, mostly involving water, and both men and women preferred lubrication during sex. After explaining what microbicides are and demonstrating them with lubricant gel, participants showed high hypothetical acceptance of microbicide use.

Contraceptive Vaginal Ring

We conducted an open label single-centre randomised clinical trial of intermittent versus continuous use of NuvaRing® in Kigali, Rwanda, in 2013–2014. We randomised 120 HIV-negative women 1:1 to intermittent use (three rings with a ring-free week in between rings) or continuous use (four rings without ring-free weeks). Women underwent an interview, counselling, and a speculum examination, and were tested for pregnancy, bacterial vaginosis (BV) by Nugent scoring, yeasts and trichomonads on wet mount, and sexually transmitted infections.

EDCTP Research

The high burden of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) and vaginal infections worldwide, but particularly in sub-Saharan Africa, has long been recognised by the World Health Organisation. In an effort to control such infections in resource-poor settings with no or limited laboratory infrastructure, the so-called ‘syndromic management guidelines’ were launched in 1978.

Get in touch

What is Rinda Ubuzima?

Rinda Ubuzima is a Rwandan non-governmental organization (NGO) specializing in clinical research, particularly in HIV prevention, reproductive health, and malaria. It evolved from the former Projet Ubuzima and has been operating a research clinic and laboratory in Kigali since 2004.

What is the mission of Rinda Ubuzima?

The mission of Rinda Ubuzima is to execute all activities aiming to promote health in Rwanda. This includes conducting clinical research, contributing to capacity building in clinical research, and implementing health promotion activities through community engagement and outreach.

What types of studies does Rinda Ubuzima conduct?

Rinda Ubuzima conducts various clinical studies focusing on HIV prevention, reproductive health, and malaria. Some of their ongoing studies include the Karisma Study, Dapivirine Ring Study, and Vibri Study.

How does Rinda Ubuzima engage with the community?

Rinda Ubuzima places a strong emphasis on community engagement and outreach. They conduct health promotion activities, collaborate with local health authorities, and involve community members in their research initiatives to ensure culturally sensitive and effective interventions.

Does Rinda Ubuzima collaborate with other organizations?

Yes, Rinda Ubuzima collaborates with various national and international stakeholders, including the Rwanda Ministry of Health and other partners, to implement programs that tackle public health issues.

How can I participate in Rinda Ubuzima's studies or programs?

Individuals interested in participating in Rinda Ubuzima's studies or programs can contact their research clinic in Kigali. Participation typically involves meeting specific eligibility criteria, which are outlined for each study.

Where can I find more information about Rinda Ubuzima's work?

For more information about Rinda Ubuzima's research, ongoing studies, and community programs, you can visit their official website at rindaubuzima.rw.
